  <div class="col-md-8">
    <p> We arrived half an hour after flooding and, thanks to the good west wind, we could still see the blowholes in action. It is a few hundred meters from the parking lot to the Pancake Rocks through rainforest. The path there only takes as much space as a person needs. To the left and right of only untouched nature. Then suddenly you stand in front of the rock formations. The Pancake Rocks are called that because they look like someone stacked several oversized pancakes on top of each other. </p>
    <p> In addition, there are also several caves, channels and gaps between rocks. These then create these water fountains. A wave breaks in a cave from one direction and creates spray. From a second direction there is a wave and increases the water level so suddenly that the pressure upwards becomes so strong that the spray is pressed out through the rock column. Really a nice sight and you can hear very well what pressure behind it. </p>
    <p> After some time and countless photos we continued towards Greymouth where we had searched for two free campsites. The first was very modest at a busy intersection and was almost full. So we decided to park again in a parking lot on the beach in the hope that the wind will let up a little. </p>
